71
00:03:49,164 --> 00:03:49,804
[SPEAKER_01]: Go ahead, Janelle.

72
00:03:51,005 --> 00:03:51,766
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you for joining us.

73
00:03:51,786 --> 00:03:52,146
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

74
00:03:52,566 --> 00:03:53,667
[SPEAKER_02]: Can everyone hear me okay?

75
00:03:54,701 --> 00:03:55,422
[SPEAKER_08]: It's great.

76
00:03:55,982 --> 00:03:57,764
[SPEAKER_02]: Nice to be with all of you this evening.

77
00:03:57,844 --> 00:03:58,985
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you for having me.

78
00:04:00,227 --> 00:04:06,273
[SPEAKER_02]: Francis was nice enough to invite me to your meeting tonight just to give an overview of the open meeting law.

79
00:04:06,853 --> 00:04:11,878
[SPEAKER_02]: I know many of you are probably very familiar with the open meeting law and what it requires.

80
00:04:13,400 --> 00:04:17,624
[SPEAKER_02]: I always think it's a good, good idea to do a refresher every couple of years.

81
00:04:17,824 --> 00:04:18,425
[SPEAKER_02]: It doesn't hurt.

82
00:04:19,755 --> 00:04:28,818
[SPEAKER_02]: The law, while it doesn't change fundamentally very often, there are things the past couple of years that have come up.

83
00:04:28,898 --> 00:04:35,361
[SPEAKER_02]: There's also been a variety of items to so-called flag or identify for all of the members this evening.

84
00:04:35,881 --> 00:04:39,322
[SPEAKER_02]: So it's really going to be an overview of the legal requirements.

85
00:04:40,334 --> 00:04:45,175
[SPEAKER_02]: Certainly, if you have any questions, this is going to be an overview of the topic.

86
00:04:45,656 --> 00:04:46,996
[SPEAKER_02]: There's a lot here.

87
00:04:47,876 --> 00:04:57,599
[SPEAKER_02]: And so if there are any specific questions, particularly where this is a public meeting, I would ask that you reach out to Francis directly to ask those questions and then

88
00:04:58,139 --> 00:05:04,561
[SPEAKER_02]: I'd be certainly happy to get back to any member directly on their questions, if that works for everyone this evening.

89
00:05:05,241 --> 00:05:07,942
[SPEAKER_02]: Frances, is there an ability for me to do a screen share?

90
00:05:07,962 --> 00:05:11,262
[SPEAKER_02]: I do have a presentation that I just wanted to go over.

91
00:05:11,943 --> 00:05:12,963
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, certainly.

92
00:05:13,183 --> 00:05:16,604
[SPEAKER_06]: Sorry, I did not think of that earlier.

93
00:05:17,064 --> 00:05:19,084
[SPEAKER_06]: All right, you should be able to now.

94
00:05:19,805 --> 00:05:20,845
[SPEAKER_06]: Great, thank you so much.

95
00:05:32,981 --> 00:05:34,142
[SPEAKER_08]: Can everyone see that okay?

96
00:05:37,304 --> 00:05:37,524
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes?

97
00:05:37,864 --> 00:05:38,084
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes.

98
00:05:38,745 --> 00:05:39,265
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, great.

99
00:05:40,686 --> 00:05:45,689
[SPEAKER_02]: So we're here to really go over the current trends and an overview of the open meeting law.

100
00:05:46,630 --> 00:05:51,433
[SPEAKER_02]: Like I said, if there are, we do work as council for the city of Medford.

101
00:05:51,513 --> 00:05:55,596
[SPEAKER_02]: If there are any specific questions, feel free to reach out directly to Francis on that.

102
00:05:57,377 --> 00:06:12,770
[SPEAKER_02]: But really wanted to go over this in in sort of a broad brush in terms of, you know, what, what is the open meeting law, what is the public records law that's a whole other different statute that we're not going to go in in detail tonight, but certainly wanted to make everyone aware of it.

103
00:06:13,530 --> 00:06:22,117
[SPEAKER_02]: And I will make a copy of this available to Frances if she wants to circulate it, because it's always a good idea just to have a reference document.

104
00:06:22,898 --> 00:06:26,081
[SPEAKER_02]: Open meeting law and public records are what we call sunshine laws.

105
00:06:26,141 --> 00:06:40,513
[SPEAKER_02]: They're really to, you know, put sunshine on the government and show how transparent the government is doing, what your public body is doing on behalf of the community, and really to identify and allow members of the public

106
00:06:40,957 --> 00:06:43,358
[SPEAKER_02]: to see what happens at all of your meetings.

107
00:06:43,838 --> 00:06:59,903
[SPEAKER_02]: And so that's really the public purpose of the open meeting law, to make sure that public business is conducted, you know, without these, with the exception of these narrow reasons, which we'll talk about in a little bit, you know, in a way that members of the public can really see what transpires.

108
00:07:00,183 --> 00:07:08,206
[SPEAKER_02]: And while there's not an obligation to have them participate, to certainly have them see what government is doing in your community.

109
00:07:10,862 --> 00:07:20,686
[SPEAKER_02]: So the open meeting law really covers a couple of different topics, you know what type we're going to cover tonight, you know what types of meetings are subject to the law.

110
00:07:21,306 --> 00:07:33,070
[SPEAKER_02]: What rules need to be followed to hold a meeting and what are some common violations and why we work with cities and towns across the Commonwealth, and so you see sort of trends in terms of.

111
00:07:33,637 --> 00:07:37,378
[SPEAKER_02]: you know, what needs to be followed and potential violations.

112
00:07:37,958 --> 00:07:47,362
[SPEAKER_02]: And I say that not to certainly scare any members here this evening, but just to make sure everyone's aware of what the law does require to make sure there's compliance with the open meeting law.

113
00:07:50,983 --> 00:07:55,364
[SPEAKER_02]: So the open meeting law addresses essentially four major issues.

114
00:07:55,504 --> 00:08:03,207
[SPEAKER_02]: And that is, again, all in this construct and this belief that things should open in a transparent manner.

115
00:08:03,867 --> 00:08:09,869
[SPEAKER_02]: So what we do know is the open meeting law requires that your meetings be noticed, right?

116
00:08:09,889 --> 00:08:11,210
[SPEAKER_02]: That there's a meeting agenda.

117
00:08:11,530 --> 00:08:15,992
[SPEAKER_02]: And we know that the timing for those is no less than 48 week day outdoors prior.

118
00:08:16,712 --> 00:08:29,217
[SPEAKER_02]: We know that the location has to be an accessible location and it has to be posted in a location that's accessible 24 hours a day, including the city's website.

119
00:08:30,189 --> 00:08:46,490
[SPEAKER_02]: And that any virtual or remote information also be accessible to members of the public, but also be able to be accessed by any member of the public that would want to attend a meeting, whether it's held in person or of course virtually as we are this evening.

120
00:08:47,833 --> 00:08:50,416
[SPEAKER_02]: So it also talks about what the nature of a meeting is.

121
00:08:50,856 --> 00:08:59,444
[SPEAKER_02]: There is a presumption, you'll hear me talk about this a lot this evening, that there's what we call an open meeting, which is what we're having this evening.

122
00:08:59,504 --> 00:09:02,688
[SPEAKER_02]: It's a meeting where members of the public can come in and listen to your meeting.

123
00:09:03,648 --> 00:09:12,177
[SPEAKER_02]: There's also a closed session or executive session, which is for very narrow purposes of when there's,

124
00:09:12,922 --> 00:09:16,023
[SPEAKER_02]: a notion that something has to maintain its confidentiality.

125
00:09:16,163 --> 00:09:30,827
[SPEAKER_02]: So we'll talk about that, but there's a presumption that your public body will conduct its business in open session, allowing members of the public to see what happens and follow any business that's conducted essentially in real time.

126
00:09:32,367 --> 00:09:35,988
[SPEAKER_02]: So the conduct of a meeting, whoops, lost my,

127
00:09:37,098 --> 00:09:45,783
[SPEAKER_02]: The conduct of a meeting there's a difference between a meeting and a hearing, so a meeting is is what we're having this evening it's to conduct public business it's to really.

128
00:09:47,044 --> 00:09:49,666
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, ensure that that your Commission is is.

129
00:09:50,619 --> 00:09:53,520
[SPEAKER_02]: conducting and reviewing matters within this jurisdiction.

130
00:09:53,540 --> 00:10:01,782
[SPEAKER_02]: A hearing is a public hearing on a liquor license, for instance, or a zoning or a land use matter.

131
00:10:01,862 --> 00:10:04,122
[SPEAKER_02]: So there's a difference between a meeting and a hearing.

132
00:10:04,422 --> 00:10:08,043
[SPEAKER_02]: And you may have circumstances where you have a meeting, but it's not a hearing.

133
00:10:08,623 --> 00:10:09,863
[SPEAKER_02]: And why is that important?

134
00:10:10,003 --> 00:10:13,044
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, at a public hearing, there is public input.

135
00:10:13,575 --> 00:10:19,038
[SPEAKER_02]: There's often a chance for both opponents and proponents to speak at that public hearing.

136
00:10:19,558 --> 00:10:21,560
[SPEAKER_02]: And there may be different legal requirements.

137
00:10:21,720 --> 00:10:24,881
[SPEAKER_02]: So I always say we should know if we're going into a meeting or a hearing.

138
00:10:26,522 --> 00:10:29,244
[SPEAKER_02]: We know that we can have remote and hybrid meetings.

139
00:10:29,344 --> 00:10:32,866
[SPEAKER_02]: Certainly that was allowable before for commissions again.

140
00:10:34,023 --> 00:10:34,824
[SPEAKER_02]: for your commission.

141
00:10:35,184 --> 00:10:44,410
[SPEAKER_02]: We also know that since 2020, as a result of COVID legislation, we've extended the ability for everyone to have remote meetings if they so choose until 2025.

142
00:10:44,570 --> 00:10:46,471
[SPEAKER_02]: And we'll talk about that.

143
00:10:47,272 --> 00:10:51,975
[SPEAKER_02]: Some public bodies are meeting completely remotely, as we are this evening.

144
00:10:52,175 --> 00:10:55,557
[SPEAKER_02]: Some are meeting in person and some are meeting in what we call a hybrid state.

145
00:10:56,809 --> 00:11:02,971
[SPEAKER_02]: We also know that the open meeting law requires that you prepare, as you just did, discuss your meeting minutes.

146
00:11:03,831 --> 00:11:12,854
[SPEAKER_02]: We know that the meeting minutes have to basically allow someone who is not present at your meeting to show or to know what was discussed.

147
00:11:13,995 --> 00:11:21,377
[SPEAKER_02]: We know that it has to indicate who attended your meeting, any votes that were taken, the date and time and the location of the meeting.

148
00:11:22,010 --> 00:11:33,116
[SPEAKER_02]: And basically, while it doesn't have to be a transcript, it does have to provide, I always say, if someone was at home and they're reviewing the meeting minutes, would they understand what transpired at a meeting?

149
00:11:33,176 --> 00:11:35,117
[SPEAKER_02]: Would they get a sense of what took place?

150
00:11:35,157 --> 00:11:36,778
[SPEAKER_02]: Would they understand what you reviewed?

151
00:11:36,798 --> 00:11:46,504
[SPEAKER_02]: And I call it, you know, the sort of four corners document, like you're looking at it and you're like, even though I wasn't there, I know what took place.

152
00:11:46,904 --> 00:11:48,885
[SPEAKER_02]: But a transcript is not required.

153
00:11:49,766 --> 00:11:55,250
[SPEAKER_02]: We know that minutes have to be approved within three meetings or 30 days, whichever is later.

154
00:11:55,710 --> 00:11:57,451
[SPEAKER_02]: Some public bodies meet very often.

155
00:11:58,011 --> 00:11:59,853
[SPEAKER_02]: Others might meet more sporadically.

156
00:12:00,253 --> 00:12:03,975
[SPEAKER_02]: We know that that's the general timeframe for approval of your meeting minutes.

157
00:12:04,836 --> 00:12:10,559
[SPEAKER_02]: And we know that their open meeting minutes will then be made publicly available.

158
00:12:11,100 --> 00:12:15,803
[SPEAKER_02]: And executive session meeting minutes, if you have an executive session, can be kept confidential

159
00:12:16,468 --> 00:12:21,836
[SPEAKER_02]: until the purpose of that confidentiality or the purpose of that executive session has been served.

160
00:12:22,397 --> 00:12:23,919
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's a little bit of an overview.

161
00:12:26,483 --> 00:12:29,248
[SPEAKER_02]: One thing that I always like to identify for

162
00:12:30,326 --> 00:12:32,967
[SPEAKER_02]: member community members is subcommittees.

163
00:12:32,987 --> 00:12:34,788
[SPEAKER_02]: This question comes up all the time.

164
00:12:34,808 --> 00:12:42,651
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, there's a particular task force or working group that may want to be formed to advise your commission.

165
00:12:42,771 --> 00:12:54,335
[SPEAKER_02]: And I always caution that no matter what it's called, even if it's called a working group or a task force or a subcommittee, there are potentially open meeting law considerations.

166
00:12:54,615 --> 00:12:59,577
[SPEAKER_02]: And so you want to look in terms of how that subcommittee or group was formed.

167
00:13:00,540 --> 00:13:11,092
[SPEAKER_02]: And, you know, if there is a group or subcommittee formed by your commission, then you would have to post and keep minutes in compliance with the open meeting law.

168
00:13:12,253 --> 00:13:14,756
[SPEAKER_02]: One person does not constitute a subcommittee.

169
00:13:14,896 --> 00:13:20,302
[SPEAKER_02]: And so, you know, if Tom says, I would like someone to look at this issue and report back,

170
00:13:20,945 --> 00:13:22,487
[SPEAKER_02]: that would not be a subcommittee.

171
00:13:22,647 --> 00:13:32,957
[SPEAKER_02]: But if there's a group of individuals that you vote to look into a particular matter within your jurisdiction, then a subcommittee would likely be triggered under the open meeting law.

172
00:13:33,238 --> 00:13:41,406
[SPEAKER_02]: And that is something we're seeing come up a lot as people try to work through different business matters for their particular public body.

173
00:13:44,682 --> 00:13:49,524
[SPEAKER_02]: So we talked a little bit about notice requirements, but I think it's always good to emphasize.

174
00:13:50,844 --> 00:13:59,267
[SPEAKER_02]: Nearly all meetings must be posted not less than 40 weekday hours prior to the date of the meeting, so the weekends and holidays don't

175
00:14:01,242 --> 00:14:04,003
[SPEAKER_02]: You cannot take those into account when you're posting your meeting.

176
00:14:04,703 --> 00:14:10,746
[SPEAKER_02]: The meeting notice must list all of the topics to be discussed with specificity, including executive sessions.

177
00:14:10,766 --> 00:14:14,207
[SPEAKER_02]: And we'll talk about that in a little bit more detail in a second.

178
00:14:15,288 --> 00:14:24,232
[SPEAKER_02]: Regardless of whether a meeting was posted correctly, a meeting occurs if there's a quorum of the public body discussing matters within its jurisdiction.

179
00:14:24,252 --> 00:14:28,774
[SPEAKER_02]: And we'll talk a lot about email tonight, but essentially,

180
00:14:30,229 --> 00:14:42,490
[SPEAKER_02]: All of the members of the commission want to ensure that they're not, you know, constantly emailing about something within their jurisdiction that could then constitute a deliberation on something that should occur at a public meeting.

181
00:14:44,145 --> 00:14:53,069
[SPEAKER_02]: I always like to call to identify some sort of tips to stay out of trouble or some items that we see come up quite often.

182
00:14:53,089 --> 00:15:03,173
[SPEAKER_02]: If any of you are attending a meeting of another body or a social event, you want to create the appearance that you're discussing any city business.

183
00:15:04,313 --> 00:15:07,615
[SPEAKER_02]: I can't tell you how many times I've received a call or

184
00:15:08,533 --> 00:15:13,494
[SPEAKER_02]: you know, seeing an allegation of a complaint, that there's a social event or a community event.

185
00:15:13,554 --> 00:15:23,077
[SPEAKER_02]: And I'm sure all of you are very involved in Medford, where there's people talking in the corner or people talking on a bench or at a particular event.

186
00:15:23,117 --> 00:15:28,918
[SPEAKER_02]: And there's this, you know, thought that somehow it relates to commission business or a public body's business.

187
00:15:29,378 --> 00:15:30,839
[SPEAKER_02]: So you really just want to be careful.

188
00:15:30,979 --> 00:15:36,720
[SPEAKER_02]: Of course, everyone is allowed to participate in their community, talk to your other

189
00:15:37,484 --> 00:15:49,489
[SPEAKER_02]: commission members, how, you know, how are your friends, how are your family, et cetera, but you really want to avoid creating the appearance that you're discussing city business on matters within your jurisdiction.

190
00:15:49,969 --> 00:16:04,115
[SPEAKER_02]: If you're attending another meeting of a public body, if you go to a city council meeting or another particular meeting, again, you just want to avoid the notion that there's a deliberation or discussion on something that you are reviewing.

191
00:16:04,643 --> 00:16:09,366
[SPEAKER_02]: that hasn't been posted, that it's not a meeting without a posting, so to speak.

192
00:16:10,587 --> 00:16:15,611
[SPEAKER_02]: Of course, there are times where you will want to meet with other public bodies perhaps.

193
00:16:16,732 --> 00:16:21,115
[SPEAKER_02]: And so the best practice would be just to post a joint meeting to be held at the same time and place.

194
00:16:22,075 --> 00:16:28,700
[SPEAKER_02]: And certainly that would avoid any issue if members of the commission wanna discuss a particular matter.

195
00:16:29,460 --> 00:16:30,601
[SPEAKER_02]: Email is a big thing.

196
00:16:30,621 --> 00:16:32,302
[SPEAKER_02]: We're gonna talk about email in a little bit,

197
00:16:33,300 --> 00:16:39,367
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, if you can avoid email on matters that are before the Commission, it's certainly a best practice.

198
00:16:46,574 --> 00:16:47,996
[SPEAKER_08]: Oh, there we go.

199
00:16:49,277 --> 00:16:50,338
[SPEAKER_02]: So email.

200
00:16:51,320 --> 00:16:55,264
[SPEAKER_02]: Email is explicitly addressed in the Open Meeting Law.

201
00:16:56,087 --> 00:17:14,793
[SPEAKER_02]: And what we know is that a quorum of the commission may not use emails to share ideas, beliefs, opinions, concerns, either as a group, I call it the reply all situation, or to one member who then forwards it to another member and then forwards it to another member.

202
00:17:15,213 --> 00:17:24,516
[SPEAKER_02]: So you really wanna be aware of reply all to emails and also kind of caution your fellow members to not

203
00:17:25,520 --> 00:17:29,322
[SPEAKER_02]: to not send emails on matters that should be discussed at a meeting.

204
00:17:29,702 --> 00:17:42,307
[SPEAKER_02]: You really wanna limit use of email to scheduling purposes and try to avoid using email, whether personal or a city email account, to undertake city business based on your positions.

205
00:17:43,227 --> 00:17:48,369
[SPEAKER_02]: You certainly wanna assume that an email may be forwarded to unintended recipients.

206
00:17:49,430 --> 00:17:52,171
[SPEAKER_02]: They also would be, if they're sent in your capacity,

207
00:17:52,824 --> 00:17:56,045
[SPEAKER_02]: As a commission member, they would be subject to the public records law.

208
00:17:56,065 --> 00:17:58,186
[SPEAKER_02]: So just to consider that.

209
00:17:59,506 --> 00:18:07,549
[SPEAKER_02]: And certainly you don't wanna ask for any other member to express their opinions, ideas, or feelings to other members as well.

210
00:18:07,849 --> 00:18:14,431
[SPEAKER_02]: So best approach is to be very cautious about email and certainly limit use to scheduling purposes.

211
00:18:14,891 --> 00:18:17,472
[SPEAKER_02]: I can meet on Tuesday, this time works for me.

212
00:18:17,492 --> 00:18:20,253
[SPEAKER_02]: And maybe it's an email from,

213
00:18:20,753 --> 00:18:24,214
[SPEAKER_02]: from one person to the other without a reply all situation.

214
00:18:25,294 --> 00:18:33,717
[SPEAKER_02]: We've all gotten so used to using email and technology for so many things, it's second nature almost to just reply and what about this?

215
00:18:33,957 --> 00:18:39,939
[SPEAKER_02]: So it's just something to be cautious about.

216
00:18:40,319 --> 00:18:42,339
[SPEAKER_02]: The same rule would apply to social media.

217
00:18:43,440 --> 00:18:44,900
[SPEAKER_02]: Certainly individuals have

218
00:18:45,491 --> 00:18:50,175
[SPEAKER_02]: their own rights, you know, in your individual capacity to use social media.

219
00:18:50,535 --> 00:18:52,697
[SPEAKER_02]: And we're not talking about any of that tonight.

220
00:18:53,618 --> 00:19:04,387
[SPEAKER_02]: But what we are talking about is, again, if there's these serial communications or directing comments to another member, if something's pending before your commission.

221
00:19:04,727 --> 00:19:06,889
[SPEAKER_02]: So that may be, you know,

222
00:19:07,657 --> 00:19:23,828
[SPEAKER_02]: someone comments on a particular project or a particular matter and then on Twitter two other members respond and then two more respond and then you now have a quorum of your commission commenting on something that really should be discussed at an open meeting.

223
00:19:23,848 --> 00:19:27,731
[SPEAKER_02]: So I just wanted to flag those as well for you.

224
00:19:30,253 --> 00:19:31,273
[SPEAKER_02]: Conducting the meeting.

225
00:19:33,511 --> 00:19:47,977
[SPEAKER_02]: This is something that I get a lot of questions about, and we talk about sunshine laws a lot and government transparency, but the open meeting law actually does not require public participation or public comment.

226
00:19:49,738 --> 00:19:54,660
[SPEAKER_02]: What we do know is if there's a public hearing, public participation is required.

227
00:19:55,860 --> 00:20:03,163
[SPEAKER_02]: What the open meeting law requires is that essentially the chair has the sole discretion as to whom they speak at a meeting and for how long.

228
00:20:04,642 --> 00:20:15,988
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, we will talk a little bit about there was a recent decision from the Supreme Judicial Court, which is the highest state court in Massachusetts that talked a lot about public comment during public meetings.

229
00:20:17,128 --> 00:20:26,053
[SPEAKER_02]: But what we know is if public comment is allowed, certainly we wouldn't want to make any restrictions based on someone's particular message or their comment.

230
00:20:27,342 --> 00:20:35,590
[SPEAKER_02]: You know if everyone has three minutes to speak or five minutes to speak during a 15 minute public comment period that's one thing.

231
00:20:36,491 --> 00:20:47,282
[SPEAKER_02]: But if one individual gets to speak for longer because of the content of his or her speech and the other person doesn't that could implicate constitutional considerations so.

232
00:20:48,230 --> 00:20:51,372
[SPEAKER_02]: just wanted to make sure everyone was aware of that.

233
00:20:51,412 --> 00:20:53,274
[SPEAKER_02]: But that is a question I get a lot.

234
00:20:53,894 --> 00:20:59,899
[SPEAKER_02]: Most public bodies I work with have public comment on their agenda, but it is not required.

235
00:21:00,019 --> 00:21:05,703
[SPEAKER_02]: And it may be that it's allowed for one meeting and not another meeting, depending on how much business you have to conduct.

236
00:21:09,080 --> 00:21:15,183
[SPEAKER_02]: So whether or not to allow public participation is a policy decision.

237
00:21:15,203 --> 00:21:22,587
[SPEAKER_02]: So it's something usually members will review and it has these implications.

238
00:21:23,507 --> 00:21:24,408
[SPEAKER_02]: When will it occur?

239
00:21:24,548 --> 00:21:25,628
[SPEAKER_02]: How long will it be?

240
00:21:25,788 --> 00:21:28,470
[SPEAKER_02]: How long will each person be permitted to speak?

241
00:21:29,650 --> 00:21:32,372
[SPEAKER_02]: And whether people will be permitted to speak more than once.

242
00:21:33,081 --> 00:21:55,918
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, I recommend that if you're going to consider allowing public comment, that these content neutral, we call them, so it's not based on what a person's saying, these general policy considerations be thought about, you know, prior to allowing it, just so everyone's on the same page, both members and also members of the public, so it's clear if there is a public comment period.

243
00:22:00,755 --> 00:22:12,428
[SPEAKER_02]: So we talked a little bit about constitutional principles for restricting public comment, but some some items to consider and certainly you'll have all of this for.

244
00:22:13,589 --> 00:22:21,217
[SPEAKER_02]: Your meetings going forward, but you know avoid debate certainly Members would want to avoid responding to a comment.

245
00:22:21,836 --> 00:22:27,079
[SPEAKER_02]: before you've had the opportunity to discuss it or if the matter is particularly controversial.

246
00:22:28,019 --> 00:22:39,045
[SPEAKER_02]: That has open meeting law considerations because you can't comment on something that isn't on the agenda generally, unless it's truly unanticipated by the chair.

247
00:22:40,585 --> 00:22:45,568
[SPEAKER_02]: You may wanna leave matters raised during public comment or public speak period, quote, unresolved.

248
00:22:47,048 --> 00:22:52,292
[SPEAKER_02]: and place it on the agenda for an upcoming meeting when there's formal notice of the agenda item.

249
00:22:52,792 --> 00:23:01,219
[SPEAKER_02]: And it allows everyone to have the time to prepare for the meeting and certainly allows other members of the public to participate if they choose as well.

250
00:23:04,821 --> 00:23:05,422
[SPEAKER_02]: Meeting minutes.

251
00:23:05,522 --> 00:23:09,285
[SPEAKER_02]: So meeting minutes are something I get a lot of questions about.

252
00:23:09,845 --> 00:23:14,749
[SPEAKER_02]: It is, as you all know, a significant undertaking to do meeting minutes.

253
00:23:15,710 --> 00:23:31,357
[SPEAKER_02]: To both draft them and to approve them and you want to make sure members of the public have, you know, or have a sense of what transpired at your meetings, this is what we talked about a little bit earlier, they have to include the date time the place of the meeting and the members present or absent.

254
00:23:32,970 --> 00:23:42,815
[SPEAKER_02]: As I had mentioned, it has to include a detailed summary of the discussion of each topic to allow a person that's not present in the meeting to understand essentially what occurred.

255
00:23:43,136 --> 00:23:43,596
[SPEAKER_02]: Pick it up.

256
00:23:43,936 --> 00:23:48,619
[SPEAKER_02]: If you just moved to the city, you have never attended a meeting, you might want to attend the next one.

257
00:23:49,019 --> 00:23:52,821
[SPEAKER_02]: You want to look at the meeting minutes and say, you know, what is the commission working on at this time?

258
00:23:52,841 --> 00:23:54,462
[SPEAKER_02]: Oh, I'm really interested in that.

259
00:23:54,962 --> 00:23:56,703
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm going to attend the next meeting.

260
00:23:57,565 --> 00:24:06,329
[SPEAKER_02]: We know the meeting minutes have to have votes of the decisions made recording, um, the votes and actions taken and no secret ballots are permitted.

261
00:24:06,349 --> 00:24:08,430
[SPEAKER_02]: I know that's not something you guys would do.

262
00:24:08,450 --> 00:24:11,191
[SPEAKER_02]: Um, but I just always identify that as well.

263
00:24:12,231 --> 00:24:15,773
[SPEAKER_02]: It should also include the meeting minutes should also include a list of documents.

264
00:24:16,393 --> 00:24:21,375
[SPEAKER_02]: If you are presented a study, a memo, a report from a city employee or official.

265
00:24:22,120 --> 00:24:30,065
[SPEAKER_02]: And it's something that you're physically using at your meeting, you're reviewing it, you're identifying it, you're discussing it amongst your fellow members.

266
00:24:30,625 --> 00:24:33,707
[SPEAKER_02]: Certainly that should be referenced in the meeting minutes as well.

267
00:24:37,549 --> 00:24:42,372
[SPEAKER_02]: So just really wanted to give you a snapshot in terms of the approval timeframe.

268
00:24:44,033 --> 00:24:48,356
[SPEAKER_02]: Again, next three minute meetings or within 30 days, whichever is later.

269
00:24:49,177 --> 00:24:51,438
[SPEAKER_02]: And this is something that also comes up

270
00:24:51,807 --> 00:24:59,555
[SPEAKER_02]: you know, frequently minutes of open meetings are public records as of the minute they're created, regardless of whether they've been approved or not.

271
00:25:00,315 --> 00:25:12,968
[SPEAKER_02]: And so draft meeting minutes are still subject to the public records law and would need to be provided with a draft stamp on top until the meeting minutes have actually been approved by the public body.

272
00:25:16,221 --> 00:25:24,247
[SPEAKER_02]: Executive session, and I may ask Tom for feedback in terms of how many times or how often you all go into executive session.

273
00:25:24,267 --> 00:25:28,830
[SPEAKER_01]: In my three years, we've never done an executive session.

274
00:25:29,171 --> 00:25:36,156
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, so we won't spend, thank you Tom, we won't spend a ton of time on this, but it's certainly something to know.

275
00:25:36,736 --> 00:25:43,421
[SPEAKER_02]: It sounds like you don't have executive session meeting minutes, but as we talked about, there's the open session and then the executive session.

276
00:25:43,880 --> 00:25:50,624
[SPEAKER_02]: I've included a slide here if you ever need to deal with executive session meeting minutes and it comes up, you'll have that information as well.

277
00:25:53,625 --> 00:26:04,071
[SPEAKER_02]: Something else that comes up particularly if a commission is very busy or a public body has a lot of meetings or there's someone's unavailable for a meeting and they might not be able to attend.

278
00:26:04,891 --> 00:26:09,794
[SPEAKER_02]: We know that the open meeting law says that a meeting cannot just be continued from one night to the next.

279
00:26:10,549 --> 00:26:11,970
[SPEAKER_02]: unless it's again posted.

280
00:26:11,990 --> 00:26:26,602
[SPEAKER_02]: So if tonight's meeting didn't have a quorum, there wasn't enough members present or someone was unavailable, you would have to essentially repost the meeting for 48 hours from tonight.

281
00:26:27,222 --> 00:26:31,926
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's something I just wanted to just identify for you all as well.

282
00:26:32,727 --> 00:26:38,271
[SPEAKER_02]: And if you're ever dealing with other legal requirements, we have the open meeting law posting, but there may be other

283
00:26:38,821 --> 00:26:43,364
[SPEAKER_02]: advertising or posting requirements that are required by state law as well.

284
00:26:47,106 --> 00:26:49,168
[SPEAKER_02]: Some other best practices to consider.

285
00:26:50,348 --> 00:27:02,296
[SPEAKER_02]: We want to make sure that the location of the posting is accessible, that it's conspicuously visible to the public at all hours and during normal business hours as well as online.

286
00:27:02,909 --> 00:27:09,575
[SPEAKER_02]: We want to not include any acronyms or abbreviations, similar to how I had mentioned with the meeting minutes.

287
00:27:09,996 --> 00:27:17,803
[SPEAKER_02]: We want members of the public at home that may be interested in attending your meeting to be able to pick it up and really understand what is going to be discussed.

288
00:27:18,844 --> 00:27:27,693
[SPEAKER_02]: This comes up a lot for grants or government agencies that may have very long names and they're shortened, and we all may know what they mean, but

289
00:27:28,063 --> 00:27:38,705
[SPEAKER_02]: you know, it's best just to make sure you include more information for a member of the public to be able to ensure that he or she knows, you know, to attend a meeting if they're interested.

290
00:27:38,725 --> 00:27:43,986
[SPEAKER_02]: And then the meeting notice also has to have the date and time of the posting.

291
00:27:44,526 --> 00:27:50,567
[SPEAKER_02]: And if it's revised, you wanna include the original posting date as well as the revised posting date as well.

292
00:27:53,908 --> 00:27:54,028
[SPEAKER_02]: So,

293
00:27:55,785 --> 00:28:03,772
[SPEAKER_02]: We know that the meeting notice has to have a lot of specificity, you know, topics, and we'll talk about some general guidelines on that.

294
00:28:04,753 --> 00:28:18,786
[SPEAKER_02]: One question that I get a lot was from what if a chair didn't reasonably anticipate a particular matter, it was something that, you know, hasn't come to the chair's attention and it needs to be handled right away.

295
00:28:19,565 --> 00:28:26,690
[SPEAKER_02]: If a matter is truly not reasonably anticipated, no prior notice, then you can discuss it.

296
00:28:27,310 --> 00:28:47,965
[SPEAKER_02]: The best practice would be to add it to the agenda as soon as you can and show the updated date and time, but the Attorney General's Division of Open Government that enforces the open meeting law does recommend that the best practice would be to put it on for a later meeting if that's possible and include it in the posting.

297
00:28:48,392 --> 00:28:52,095
[SPEAKER_02]: So I just wanted to clarify what unanticipated means.

298
00:28:54,856 --> 00:28:56,938
[SPEAKER_02]: The other question that comes up is emergencies.

299
00:28:57,018 --> 00:28:59,920
[SPEAKER_02]: If you had a particular emergency, can that be discussed?

300
00:29:00,520 --> 00:29:01,701
[SPEAKER_02]: And the answer is yes.

301
00:29:02,802 --> 00:29:11,248
[SPEAKER_02]: But what we know from the determinations from the Attorney General's office is that doesn't include, you know, something just missed the agenda or

302
00:29:12,020 --> 00:29:20,783
[SPEAKER_02]: we were, you know, it was supposed to be put on, but for whatever reason it wasn't put on, it's truly, you know, public safety, public health, weather related emergencies.

303
00:29:21,863 --> 00:29:25,604
[SPEAKER_02]: Those are kind of the big items that we see in the emergency category.

304
00:29:27,925 --> 00:29:34,007
[SPEAKER_02]: So what we know since the open meeting law was amended now many years ago to have

305
00:29:34,545 --> 00:29:40,026
[SPEAKER_02]: the Attorney General's Office enforce it, is that placeholders, so to speak, are now a no-go.

306
00:29:40,646 --> 00:29:44,927
[SPEAKER_02]: And so more detail is better than a little bit of detail.

307
00:29:45,067 --> 00:29:51,008
[SPEAKER_02]: So we want to say, instead of new business or old business, really, what is that new business?

308
00:29:51,188 --> 00:29:52,909
[SPEAKER_02]: Are there reports that are being reviewed?

309
00:29:53,069 --> 00:29:54,849
[SPEAKER_02]: Is there an initiative being reviewed?

310
00:29:55,349 --> 00:30:01,691
[SPEAKER_02]: Really just spell out for members of the public what is going to be discussed so that they can attend if they choose to.

311
00:30:02,811 --> 00:30:03,451
[SPEAKER_02]: We see this on

312
00:30:04,153 --> 00:30:05,273
[SPEAKER_02]: know, agendas all the time.

313
00:30:05,293 --> 00:30:14,537
[SPEAKER_02]: I think the more detail that can be provided to the public, and the more specificity that can be included on your agenda, the better it is.

314
00:30:17,838 --> 00:30:19,819
[SPEAKER_02]: So we talked a little bit about emergencies.

315
00:30:21,079 --> 00:30:27,742
[SPEAKER_02]: If you do deal with any of these, you know, certainly, you'd want to comply with the law to the extent you can.

316
00:30:28,547 --> 00:30:37,753
[SPEAKER_02]: Um, in the past couple of years, there have been, you know, some significant public health matters that require emergency attention or weather related matters.

317
00:30:38,473 --> 00:30:44,077
[SPEAKER_02]: Um, you want to do what you can to post it up and really just focus on the emergency at hand.

318
00:30:44,097 --> 00:30:51,641
[SPEAKER_02]: You still need to take minutes of the meeting and review them in and post another meeting to say, we're review.

319
00:30:51,781 --> 00:30:57,805
[SPEAKER_02]: This was an emergency we had to meet, but in the future we're ratifying and looking at this again.

320
00:31:03,135 --> 00:31:04,536
[SPEAKER_02]: You guys did a great job tonight.

321
00:31:05,057 --> 00:31:14,825
[SPEAKER_02]: You want to make a public statement or notify members of the public that they're being recorded, you know, to ensure compliance with the mask wiretap statute.

322
00:31:15,466 --> 00:31:22,692
[SPEAKER_02]: And if an individual decides to record on their own, they would need to inform the chair.

323
00:31:22,972 --> 00:31:25,975
[SPEAKER_02]: So Tom will have to let you know, and that you would

324
00:31:26,331 --> 00:31:29,013
[SPEAKER_02]: be required to make the reasonable announcement.

325
00:31:30,674 --> 00:31:49,005
[SPEAKER_02]: If you were meeting in person or it was onerous for an individual to do it, I mean, technology is so small right now, but it used to be back in the day, the large VHS cameras, but the bottom line is no one can secretly record anyone else in Massachusetts.

326
00:31:49,145 --> 00:31:54,368
[SPEAKER_02]: So it's a good idea just to make sure everyone understands that at the beginning of a meeting.

327
00:31:57,499 --> 00:32:05,085
[SPEAKER_02]: Executive session, Tom was nice enough to clarify that you don't deal with this quite often, but certainly if you do, here's the process.

328
00:32:05,125 --> 00:32:07,827
[SPEAKER_02]: So I just wanted to make sure all of you have that information.

329
00:32:07,847 --> 00:32:22,599
[SPEAKER_02]: We know that you're gonna convene an open session, you're going to state the purpose of an executive session, and maybe someone's privacy interests, for example, or other matters, and there's a roll call vote requirement for that.

330
00:32:22,940 --> 00:32:25,842
[SPEAKER_02]: So if you ever need it, that process is right there for everyone.

331
00:32:29,861 --> 00:32:32,864
[SPEAKER_02]: Some additional executive session information.

332
00:32:33,205 --> 00:32:39,652
[SPEAKER_02]: If you are going into an executive session, then you do need to kind of clarify why you're doing it.

333
00:32:40,233 --> 00:32:47,441
[SPEAKER_02]: And again, if you have specific questions or if you ever have to deal with this, feel free to have Francis or any of you can reach out to me directly on that.

334
00:32:47,541 --> 00:32:48,182
[SPEAKER_02]: That's fine.

335
00:32:51,543 --> 00:33:02,047
[SPEAKER_02]: So I've included here, again, not to belabor the enforcement piece of this, but just so you know, if you ever see it, what the complaint process is.

336
00:33:02,627 --> 00:33:18,213
[SPEAKER_02]: Essentially, if a member of the public feels as if there has been a violation of the open meeting law, this is the complaint process that has to be filed within 30 days of the alleged violation, and then it requires review by the commission and a response.

337
00:33:19,660 --> 00:33:34,294
[SPEAKER_02]: I will say, you know, in my experience doing this work for 17, almost 17 years, there are very, very extreme and limited circumstances where fines have been issued.

338
00:33:34,815 --> 00:33:43,203
[SPEAKER_02]: So I don't want anyone to worry about that per se, but certainly something to be cognizant of and remember compliance with the open meeting law.

339
00:33:46,396 --> 00:33:54,757
[SPEAKER_02]: These are some recent notable court decisions that I like to include the Baron case that I had just mentioned that was a very recent case.

340
00:33:55,572 --> 00:34:04,775
[SPEAKER_02]: Um, it was just decided by the, the SJC, the highest court in Massachusetts this spring, um, or early spring 2023.

341
00:34:05,795 --> 00:34:09,656
[SPEAKER_02]: And essentially I just wanted to provide a summary for everyone.

342
00:34:09,676 --> 00:34:14,578
[SPEAKER_02]: And that, that dealt with really the public comment requirements that we talked about earlier.

343
00:34:14,598 --> 00:34:22,400
[SPEAKER_02]: Um, essentially, you know, in summary, while the open meeting law doesn't require a public comment period, then

344
00:34:23,272 --> 00:34:35,095
[SPEAKER_02]: you do wanna ensure that if you do have a public comment period that you're meeting the constitutional requirements and not making content-based restrictions for individual speech.

345
00:34:36,055 --> 00:34:43,156
[SPEAKER_02]: I've included a older case involving the Natick School Committee that again dealt with public comment during public meetings.

346
00:34:44,236 --> 00:34:51,878
[SPEAKER_02]: And that case held that public comment policies and practices must ensure that restrictions are again

347
00:34:52,490 --> 00:35:03,033
[SPEAKER_02]: narrowly tailored and really content, not content-based, just time of everyone had the same amount of time or could speak one time per meeting.

348
00:35:04,193 --> 00:35:09,514
[SPEAKER_02]: The Swansea case involved a sufficiency of meeting notices, so I've included that.

349
00:35:10,034 --> 00:35:16,956
[SPEAKER_02]: And the Boulder case probably isn't applicable to your commission, but certainly wanted to make sure you had all that information as well.

350
00:35:19,973 --> 00:35:24,194
[SPEAKER_02]: So the current state of the open meeting law, we get questions on this a lot.

351
00:35:25,234 --> 00:35:30,095
[SPEAKER_02]: The pandemic error changes are still in place until 2025.

352
00:35:30,735 --> 00:35:35,076
[SPEAKER_02]: That was signed into law by Governor Healey on March 29th, 2023.

353
00:35:35,676 --> 00:35:42,338
[SPEAKER_02]: So we know that the remote option for all public bodies is available as a matter of law until March 31st, 2025.

354
00:35:45,553 --> 00:35:55,959
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, essentially, instead of holding meetings at an accessible public place, then there can be adequate alternative means, such as Zoom, like we're on tonight, of public access.

355
00:35:56,960 --> 00:36:01,403
[SPEAKER_02]: We also know that public body members entirely may participate remotely.

356
00:36:02,383 --> 00:36:04,204
[SPEAKER_02]: Meetings do not need to be held remotely.

357
00:36:04,744 --> 00:36:08,987
[SPEAKER_02]: Like I said, many, many public bodies are still meeting entirely remotely.

358
00:36:10,277 --> 00:36:27,417
[SPEAKER_02]: And certainly you're all aware that outside of coven 19 related changes commissions on disabilities may decide by majority of vote to meet remotely as well, and that the mayor's authority is not required to do that, even outside of the pandemic or change.

359
00:36:32,443 --> 00:36:47,709
[SPEAKER_02]: So the one thing I just wanted to, you all seem very, very Zoom savvy, and I think we all probably are pretty tech savvy at this point, but we do need to make sure that there is what we call real-time access.

360
00:36:48,509 --> 00:36:56,793
[SPEAKER_02]: And so if there is a technical problem and we've all been there, that the live stream crashes or a meeting has to be paused,

361
00:36:58,512 --> 00:37:08,021
[SPEAKER_02]: you would wanna take a break to try to fix the tech issue essentially, but continuing a meeting and posting a recording doesn't cure a violation.

362
00:37:08,041 --> 00:37:19,653
[SPEAKER_02]: And so you really wanna make sure members of the public that are at home can certainly access the meeting in an accessible manner to allow them to follow along in real time.

363
00:37:24,851 --> 00:37:28,974
[SPEAKER_02]: Just a little checklist I provided for all the members this evening.

364
00:37:28,994 --> 00:37:41,724
[SPEAKER_02]: If we are meeting remotely like we are tonight, the recording, as you all stated at the beginning, votes would be taken by a roll call vote and meeting members should introduce themselves at the start of a meeting.

365
00:37:41,744 --> 00:37:45,347
[SPEAKER_02]: To the extent you can, camera should also be on.

366
00:37:46,431 --> 00:37:49,612
[SPEAKER_02]: If your device doesn't have a camera, then that's fine.

367
00:37:49,632 --> 00:37:56,555
[SPEAKER_02]: And it doesn't seem like you have to, you deal with executive session meeting minutes often.

368
00:37:57,415 --> 00:38:07,138
[SPEAKER_02]: But if you did, you would want to make sure that members of the, there's a statement that no other person is able to hear you or hear your discussion at the remote location.

369
00:38:07,158 --> 00:38:12,620
[SPEAKER_02]: And that is because executive sessions generally involve confidential information.

370
00:38:15,206 --> 00:38:15,827
[SPEAKER_02]: Hybrid meetings.

371
00:38:15,887 --> 00:38:18,850
[SPEAKER_02]: Tom, do you meet primarily solely remote at this point?

372
00:38:18,890 --> 00:38:19,931
[SPEAKER_02]: Are you hybrid at all?

373
00:38:19,952 --> 00:38:25,358
[SPEAKER_01]: Except for one meeting, we've been mostly remote.

374
00:38:26,836 --> 00:38:33,300
[SPEAKER_02]: So if you do have hybrid meetings, I just wanted to give you some information on that.

375
00:38:33,620 --> 00:38:37,802
[SPEAKER_02]: You can meet in person, but require members of the public to watch a live stream.

376
00:38:38,803 --> 00:38:42,005
[SPEAKER_02]: Some members may be at home, some members may be in person.

377
00:38:43,426 --> 00:38:51,831
[SPEAKER_02]: And again, the big issue that I see come up the most on this is if that live access stops for members of the public at home.

378
00:38:52,371 --> 00:38:55,653
[SPEAKER_02]: So you just wanna be careful not to deliberate if there are tech issues.

379
00:38:57,273 --> 00:39:03,655
[SPEAKER_02]: And if the tech issue is resolved, then certainly you can continue the meeting through the chair at that time.

380
00:39:08,996 --> 00:39:13,698
[SPEAKER_02]: Meetings may be held in person if you choose, but again, no requirement to do so.

381
00:39:14,658 --> 00:39:20,499
[SPEAKER_02]: If there is a meeting open to the public, then there has to be sufficient room for all of the public to attend.

382
00:39:21,600 --> 00:39:22,580
[SPEAKER_02]: And certainly, you know,

383
00:39:23,390 --> 00:39:28,051
[SPEAKER_02]: If there's a hybrid meeting, that should not be an issue.

384
00:39:28,111 --> 00:39:30,392
[SPEAKER_02]: Or if you're meeting solely remote, it shouldn't be an issue.

385
00:39:30,472 --> 00:39:39,795
[SPEAKER_02]: If you had a meeting where you had a large amount of people participating, you wanna make sure there's no restriction on the number of people that can sign into the Zoom.

386
00:39:40,115 --> 00:39:42,095
[SPEAKER_02]: I've seen that come up on particular matters.

387
00:39:42,655 --> 00:39:44,096
[SPEAKER_02]: So just check that as well.

388
00:39:45,878 --> 00:39:58,551
[SPEAKER_02]: And the Attorney General's office has also issued guidance stating that meetings can be held in a location that requires a mask if that's necessary for any members or any of the members of the public that would need that.

389
00:40:00,590 --> 00:40:02,332
[SPEAKER_02]: So I think that's about it.

390
00:40:02,372 --> 00:40:07,016
[SPEAKER_02]: I just wanted to leave time for some specific overview type questions.

391
00:40:07,076 --> 00:40:17,826
[SPEAKER_02]: And then if there's anything else after our session this evening, certainly as I had mentioned, I'm happy to work with Francis to make sure all those questions are answered.

392
00:40:17,887 --> 00:40:19,648
[SPEAKER_02]: But I appreciate all of your time tonight.

393
00:40:19,668 --> 00:40:25,454
[SPEAKER_02]: I know it's a lot of content, but I tried to kind of focus on the highlights, so to speak.

394
00:40:28,870 --> 00:40:31,171
[SPEAKER_06]: Wow, Janelle, thank you, thank you so much.

395
00:40:31,231 --> 00:40:35,514
[SPEAKER_06]: Every time I see one of these presentations, I feel like, oh my gosh, there's something else that I've missed.

396
00:40:35,554 --> 00:40:37,756
[SPEAKER_06]: Wait, have we done, have we done that?

397
00:40:38,436 --> 00:40:56,427
[SPEAKER_06]: So I, you know, I'm really excited because this time I know that we'll get the slides, which we, I feel like as the commission, we all sort of like help each other stay on track because it can be difficult to remember

398
00:40:59,065 --> 00:41:07,774
[SPEAKER_06]: I think, for me, it's the email, you know, that I just want to make sure that people are clear about.

399
00:41:08,594 --> 00:41:16,022
[SPEAKER_06]: And my other question is, you know, when when you don't have quorum, can you hold a meeting?

400
00:41:16,442 --> 00:41:16,902
[SPEAKER_06]: Because

401
00:41:20,102 --> 00:41:23,184
[SPEAKER_02]: So I get the first one, I'll go in reverse order.

402
00:41:23,264 --> 00:41:24,744
[SPEAKER_02]: The second one, thank you, Francis.

403
00:41:24,764 --> 00:41:25,805
[SPEAKER_02]: Those are good questions.

404
00:41:26,925 --> 00:41:29,887
[SPEAKER_02]: If there's no quorum, then no, right?

405
00:41:30,487 --> 00:41:36,850
[SPEAKER_02]: Because the commission has to meet when it has a quorum and take action as a public body as a quorum.

406
00:41:36,950 --> 00:41:42,452
[SPEAKER_02]: So you'd wanna continue that meeting and essentially repost it if you don't have a quorum.

407
00:41:42,773 --> 00:41:43,393
[SPEAKER_02]: The email,

408
00:41:44,128 --> 00:41:53,410
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, again, we all rely on technology and email so, so much, and it does make lives easier in so many ways.

409
00:41:54,891 --> 00:41:59,852
[SPEAKER_02]: Email should really be used for scheduling.

410
00:41:59,872 --> 00:42:07,674
[SPEAKER_02]: The classic example I use is if a member wants to put a particular item on an agenda.

411
00:42:07,934 --> 00:42:09,614
[SPEAKER_02]: I wanna talk about this report.

412
00:42:10,234 --> 00:42:13,115
[SPEAKER_02]: I wanna talk about this particular community matter.

413
00:42:13,960 --> 00:42:26,043
[SPEAKER_02]: what they should do is really just email either yourself, Francis, or Tom and say, this is something I would like to review at the meeting on, you know, our next meeting in June.

414
00:42:26,403 --> 00:42:26,883
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

415
00:42:27,823 --> 00:42:36,105
[SPEAKER_02]: Because the risk is always, if it goes to the entire public body, it's everyone, we're all nice people.

416
00:42:36,165 --> 00:42:37,305
[SPEAKER_02]: We all want to be helpful.

417
00:42:37,765 --> 00:42:40,646
[SPEAKER_02]: There's a natural instinct for someone to reply to say,

418
00:42:41,234 --> 00:42:57,133
[SPEAKER_02]: And i'm not saying any of you have done this, but this is you know what comes up from time to time, I think that's a great idea, or I talked to this person and they they thought it was a good idea let's prioritize X, and then we can prioritize why.

419
00:42:58,292 --> 00:43:01,114
[SPEAKER_02]: Should we bring this person into the meeting?

420
00:43:01,214 --> 00:43:06,957
[SPEAKER_02]: Or do you think this community member might have some additional feedback or information that might be helpful to the commission?

421
00:43:07,517 --> 00:43:10,439
[SPEAKER_02]: It all comes from an entirely good place, right?

422
00:43:10,899 --> 00:43:16,362
[SPEAKER_02]: But the issue is all of that under the open meeting law should be happening at an open meeting.

423
00:43:17,202 --> 00:43:25,386
[SPEAKER_02]: And so the best practice would be, again, to email yourself or to email Tom to say, can we put this on the agenda for June?

424
00:43:25,987 --> 00:43:26,707
[SPEAKER_02]: I think that

425
00:43:27,770 --> 00:43:33,015
[SPEAKER_02]: Janelle Austin might have something to add, or this report might be something that may be of interest.

426
00:43:34,756 --> 00:43:43,864
[SPEAKER_02]: It would probably be easier for a staff, you know, for Francis instead of a board member to do it, but information can be shared in advance of the meeting.

427
00:43:44,585 --> 00:43:47,087
[SPEAKER_02]: It just can't be commented on, right?

428
00:43:47,227 --> 00:43:50,189
[SPEAKER_02]: And so no expression of beliefs, opinions.

429
00:43:51,711 --> 00:43:53,773
[SPEAKER_02]: So sometimes I will see chairs

430
00:43:54,978 --> 00:44:02,164
[SPEAKER_02]: or liaison right on the bottom of an email, please see materials for June, 2023 meeting.

431
00:44:02,945 --> 00:44:09,470
[SPEAKER_02]: Here's the agenda, you know, for your information, please do not discuss in advance of the meeting or for discussion only.

432
00:44:09,490 --> 00:44:14,254
[SPEAKER_02]: And some public bodies I work with even go so far as to say, please do not reply all.

433
00:44:14,674 --> 00:44:21,800
[SPEAKER_02]: Like, please remember the open, because it's like, you know, everyone sees the email or they'll see a text message and they'll just reply.

434
00:44:22,540 --> 00:44:27,502
[SPEAKER_02]: And so it can just be as simple as, you know, please see the materials.

435
00:44:27,822 --> 00:44:29,343
[SPEAKER_02]: Please remember the open meeting lot.

436
00:44:29,383 --> 00:44:30,544
[SPEAKER_02]: Please do not reply.

437
00:44:30,564 --> 00:44:32,344
[SPEAKER_02]: We'll discuss it at our next meeting.

438
00:44:32,905 --> 00:44:40,548
[SPEAKER_02]: And that is just a natural reminder for everyone to say this is something we'll talk about in a public meeting when we meet next.

439
00:44:40,568 --> 00:44:48,712
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, the other question is, I get a lot, is well, can we, you know, collaborate on meeting minutes?

440
00:44:48,852 --> 00:44:49,212
[SPEAKER_02]: Can we

441
00:44:49,797 --> 00:44:54,778
[SPEAKER_02]: If someone sends a Google Drive to meeting minutes, can we all put our changes in in advance?

442
00:44:56,258 --> 00:45:05,960
[SPEAKER_02]: And we know that the attorney general's office has said no, because everyone's sharing their ideas or beliefs on what happened at that meeting outside of the meeting.

443
00:45:07,300 --> 00:45:14,381
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's another question that technology has put a wrinkle in things, so to speak.

444
00:45:14,521 --> 00:45:18,282
[SPEAKER_02]: But that's really what I think is the best practice

445
00:45:19,304 --> 00:45:20,845
[SPEAKER_02]: on email if that's possible.

446
00:45:23,325 --> 00:45:24,546
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you so much, Janelle.

447
00:45:25,046 --> 00:45:25,866
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Frances.

448
00:45:26,046 --> 00:45:27,287
[SPEAKER_02]: Did you have a question, Tom?

449
00:45:28,287 --> 00:45:28,727
[SPEAKER_01]: I do.

450
00:45:28,827 --> 00:45:31,128
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Janelle.

451
00:45:31,488 --> 00:45:32,989
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you for sharing all this information.

452
00:45:33,069 --> 00:45:37,090
[SPEAKER_01]: It's a lot of good information, I think new information for us.

453
00:45:39,091 --> 00:45:41,211
[SPEAKER_01]: And Frances, thank you for having Janelle come.

454
00:45:41,272 --> 00:45:43,652
[SPEAKER_01]: I think this is something you've been asking for.

455
00:45:43,832 --> 00:45:46,873
[SPEAKER_01]: So I think it provides some clarity in how we interact.

456
00:45:48,907 --> 00:46:02,910
[SPEAKER_01]: I think my, excuse me, my question is how, so as an example, we are working on planning an event for the fall.

457
00:46:03,830 --> 00:46:12,592
[SPEAKER_01]: And based on what you've said, it feels like our options are limited and I'm not sure what our options are other than our monthly meeting.

458
00:46:13,210 --> 00:46:20,835
[SPEAKER_01]: to do planning for that event due to limiting interactions outside of the meeting.

459
00:46:20,855 --> 00:46:24,537
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm just curious to hear your thoughts on that.

460
00:46:25,137 --> 00:46:28,259
[SPEAKER_01]: It's kind of an example of how we communicate.

461
00:46:29,119 --> 00:46:29,440
[SPEAKER_02]: Sure.

462
00:46:29,460 --> 00:46:39,606
[SPEAKER_02]: So I think when people plan events, it may be that the public, the commission decides who is going to

463
00:46:41,292 --> 00:46:44,153
[SPEAKER_02]: you know, who is going to look at a particular matter.

464
00:46:44,333 --> 00:46:56,195
[SPEAKER_02]: So someone may be in charge of one aspect of the event, someone else may be in charge of another aspect of the event, and everyone, you know, does their own work, so to speak, and then reports back at the monthly meeting.

465
00:46:56,255 --> 00:46:56,995
[SPEAKER_02]: I've seen that.

466
00:46:58,555 --> 00:47:09,137
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, I think it is often that that is how it will work, and then updates are provided by each individual member at the meeting.

467
00:47:11,005 --> 00:47:14,788
[SPEAKER_01]: So individually, we can do things and then report back.

468
00:47:15,949 --> 00:47:22,695
[SPEAKER_01]: Is that something that they can share with me, the chair, prior to the meeting or we wait till the meeting?

469
00:47:23,366 --> 00:47:39,770
[SPEAKER_02]: You can, as long as it's not a quorum, so if it's one member directly to you, Tom, that wouldn't be a quorum deliberating outside of the meeting, as long as you then don't share it with another person who then shares it with another person who then shares it with another person.

470
00:47:41,211 --> 00:47:48,693
[SPEAKER_02]: So it does take, you know, it does take a lot of discipline from the chair, so to speak, to not,

471
00:47:51,348 --> 00:47:54,030
[SPEAKER_02]: deliberate serially, they say, right?

472
00:47:54,211 --> 00:47:56,152
[SPEAKER_02]: One person to one person to another person.

473
00:47:57,253 --> 00:48:04,599
[SPEAKER_02]: Because, you know, you'll have situations where then people come to a meeting and they're like, do you remember when the four of us were talking about this or the five of us?

474
00:48:04,659 --> 00:48:06,381
[SPEAKER_02]: And a member of the public's like, what?

475
00:48:07,201 --> 00:48:10,925
[SPEAKER_02]: So I think that's really the best practice.

476
00:48:10,945 --> 00:48:13,467
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

477
00:48:14,267 --> 00:48:14,788
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Tom.

478
00:48:17,337 --> 00:48:19,358
[SPEAKER_02]: Marsha, did you have a question?

479
00:48:19,438 --> 00:48:20,598
[SPEAKER_09]: A little bit more.

480
00:48:20,958 --> 00:48:24,459
[SPEAKER_09]: My concern is what Tom is asking about.

481
00:48:25,320 --> 00:48:38,324
[SPEAKER_09]: Is there any way to have more than one member working on an issue, communicating about it between meetings?

482
00:48:39,384 --> 00:48:41,645
[SPEAKER_09]: Planning this event is a big thing.

483
00:48:42,886 --> 00:48:46,227
[SPEAKER_09]: And if each person works on a part of it,

484
00:48:47,150 --> 00:48:55,717
[SPEAKER_09]: okay but it doesn't really work that way because there's too much for one person to do in a given area.

485
00:48:56,157 --> 00:48:58,479
[SPEAKER_09]: So you can't logically divide the area.

486
00:48:59,920 --> 00:49:05,164
[SPEAKER_09]: So is there a way that that can be handled?

487
00:49:06,605 --> 00:49:12,850
[SPEAKER_02]: So certainly the work can be divided up particularly for a larger event that wouldn't

488
00:49:13,280 --> 00:49:15,408
[SPEAKER_02]: cause any open meeting law issues.

489
00:49:15,649 --> 00:49:16,693
[SPEAKER_02]: It's really when

490
00:49:18,811 --> 00:49:24,552
[SPEAKER_02]: there's communication between what each person's doing outside of a meeting.

491
00:49:24,913 --> 00:49:27,333
[SPEAKER_02]: Like I call it the check-in, right?

492
00:49:27,533 --> 00:49:36,315
[SPEAKER_02]: So if you're working on something, Marsha, and Joe's working on something, Linda's working on something, Tom's working on something, that's fine.

493
00:49:36,675 --> 00:49:43,077
[SPEAKER_02]: As members, you can all be working on any tasks that have been divided up at a public meeting.

494
00:49:43,097 --> 00:49:46,098
[SPEAKER_02]: And maybe, you know, everyone's doing a particular thing.

495
00:49:46,618 --> 00:49:47,338
[SPEAKER_02]: That's fine.

496
00:49:48,293 --> 00:49:54,036
[SPEAKER_02]: And if you want to communicate back to Tom, this is how this is going, that's fine.

497
00:49:54,496 --> 00:50:07,803
[SPEAKER_02]: But again, these check-in type of meetings or statuses, so to speak, of this event is coming together great, you know, this vendor set up, you know, the space is reserved.

498
00:50:08,910 --> 00:50:27,760
[SPEAKER_02]: you know, I'm working on this, I expect to get an answer back on such and such a date, and you want to report that back to all of your fellow members, that should happen in an open meeting that's listed on the agenda that says, you know, event, the name of the event, planning, and discussion, right?

499
00:50:27,800 --> 00:50:29,501
[SPEAKER_02]: It doesn't have to be very long.

500
00:50:29,961 --> 00:50:37,285
[SPEAKER_02]: It just has to really, because maybe a member of the public wants to volunteer, or they want to help out, or they're really just interested in following the progress,

501
00:50:38,573 --> 00:50:40,395
[SPEAKER_02]: So everyone can do things on their own.

502
00:50:41,276 --> 00:50:50,823
[SPEAKER_02]: You just, I mean, the takeaway is really public business can't be conducted outside of an open meeting because you're a member of a public body.

503
00:50:52,144 --> 00:50:59,410
[SPEAKER_02]: So that's really the big takeaway, but I have no issue with, you know, everyone doing, no one is expected to do everything.

504
00:50:59,510 --> 00:51:03,393
[SPEAKER_02]: So everyone kind of dividing up the work and reporting that, that's fine.

505
00:51:05,395 --> 00:51:06,396
[SPEAKER_02]: Good question, Marsha.

506
00:51:10,129 --> 00:51:18,774
[SPEAKER_09]: I just, frankly, I'll comment, it makes it incredibly difficult to organize anything.

507
00:51:20,055 --> 00:51:23,076
[SPEAKER_09]: And unnecessary, it doesn't seem necessary to me.

508
00:51:23,777 --> 00:51:34,823
[SPEAKER_09]: I don't think that anyone in the public cares what specific organization I contact to get a case at this event, for example, which is something I'm trying.

509
00:51:35,583 --> 00:51:38,965
[SPEAKER_02]: Right, and it doesn't, you wouldn't have to come back

510
00:51:39,702 --> 00:51:43,144
[SPEAKER_02]: you know, at the meeting, go through each and every step you did.

511
00:51:43,164 --> 00:51:45,645
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't think that's required at all.

512
00:51:45,665 --> 00:51:53,430
[SPEAKER_02]: It would be, you know, if Tom simply said, you know, Marcia, can you update me on X, Y, and Z?

513
00:51:53,490 --> 00:51:55,331
[SPEAKER_02]: And you said, yes, I've been working on this.

514
00:51:55,631 --> 00:51:57,352
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, here's where things are at.

515
00:51:58,192 --> 00:52:00,674
[SPEAKER_02]: That's all that really would have to happen.

516
00:52:00,814 --> 00:52:05,056
[SPEAKER_02]: And then all your fellow members are aware of what you've been working on.

517
00:52:05,996 --> 00:52:08,358
[SPEAKER_02]: It just can't be, and I'm not saying this is what would happen,

518
00:52:09,428 --> 00:52:14,234
[SPEAKER_02]: It can't be picking up the phone and calling multiple people and reporting what happened.

519
00:52:14,254 --> 00:52:15,976
[SPEAKER_02]: That has to be a public meeting.

520
00:52:16,817 --> 00:52:18,800
[SPEAKER_09]: Could the co-chair help the chair?

521
00:52:20,162 --> 00:52:20,942
[SPEAKER_09]: Sorry, Linda.

522
00:52:22,164 --> 00:52:23,345
[SPEAKER_09]: It doesn't have to be you.

523
00:52:25,068 --> 00:52:28,472
[SPEAKER_09]: I'd like to know if that's possible.

524
00:52:31,112 --> 00:52:36,377
[SPEAKER_02]: A co-chair, I mean, the best practice is that it should happen, you know, like I said, at a public meeting.

525
00:52:36,397 --> 00:52:40,202
[SPEAKER_02]: But yes, tasks can be divided up.

526
00:52:41,183 --> 00:52:52,455
[SPEAKER_02]: And certainly, as long as there's not a deliberation of a quorum of members, either at the same time or serially, then the open meeting law wouldn't be implicated.

527
00:52:54,897 --> 00:53:01,303
[SPEAKER_02]: And if there's other specific questions as you guys continue to plan the event, maybe Francis or Tom could let me know.

528
00:53:01,323 --> 00:53:04,085
[SPEAKER_01]: I think that's a good idea.

529
00:53:04,766 --> 00:53:06,528
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Jim.

530
00:53:06,788 --> 00:53:08,690
[SPEAKER_01]: Linda, is there time for one more question for Linda?

531
00:53:08,710 --> 00:53:11,292
[SPEAKER_01]: And then we can move on to the next item.

532
00:53:11,673 --> 00:53:11,993
[SPEAKER_06]: Oh, yes.

533
00:53:12,033 --> 00:53:12,633
[SPEAKER_06]: Sorry, Linda.

